            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1351050229,
            "creation_date": 1351049410,
            "body": "<p>Don't do that, please. Keep it to your <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Data_access_layer\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">Data Access Layer<\/a>. Don't mess up your JSP with SQL related code.<\/p>\n\n<p>Furthermore, don't pollute your JSP with Java code. Therefore, replace the scriplets with  <a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/tags/jstl/info\">JSTL<\/a>/<a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/tags/el/info\">EL<\/a> instead.<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Simple <a href=\"http://simple.souther.us/ar01s05.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">MVC Example<\/a>, from Ben Souther, Sheriff, JavaRanch.<\/li>\n<li><a href=\"http://www.javaranch.com/journal/200603/Journal200603.jsp#a5\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">Scriptless JSP Pages<\/a>, an article from JavaRanch Journal <\/li>\n<\/ul>\n",
            "answer_id": 13042598,
            "question_id": 13042522,
            "last_edit_date": 1495541532
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/Jlp9D.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 2126926,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 1888810,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1888810/shailesh-saxena",
                "reputation": 3522,
                "display_name": "Shailesh Saxena",
                "accept_rate": 55
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1361944429,
            "creation_date": 1361944429,
            "body": "<p>According to the MVC2 rules, all the logics related to database issues should be kept in persistence layer using DB bean or Hibernate, JDO like frameworks. And all the business logics should be kept in either bean classes or spring  bean, ejb session bean component.\nIf you are using only jsp in any small application, just follow these steps:<\/p>\n\n<ol>\n<li>Create a separate simple or Bean class taking all the properties as private<\/li>\n<li>Write your logic in that class in the form of public methods<\/li>\n<li>Use <code>&lt;jsp:useBean&gt;, &lt;jsp:setProperty&gt; and &lt;jsp:getProperty&gt;<\/code> like tags in your jsp pages to    access the object of your bean class<\/li>\n<li>call the required methods of your Bean class using id(object refrence)<\/li>\n<\/ol>\n\n<p>And placing java code in jsp is not recommended, so try to use jstl or custom tags .<\/p>\n\n<p>I hope it'll help you... :)<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 15105145,
